9\. (Soil) on which Darbha-grass grows, brings holy lustre;

10\. Big sorts of grass, strength;

11\. Tender grass, cattle.

12\. Or (the site of the house) should have the form of bricks (?) or of
. . . . . . . (?)

13\. Or there should be natural holes (in the ground) in all directions.

14, 15. (A house) with its door to the east brings wealth and fame; with
its door to the north, children and cattle. By one with its door to the
south all wishes (are obtained). The back-door should not face (?) the
house-door.

16\. Milk-rice should be offered,

17\. And a black cow,

18\. Or a white goat. Or only milk-rice.

19\. In the middle of the house he should sacrifice the fat (of the
animal) and the milk-rice, mixed with Â*g*ya, taking eight portions (of
that mixture), with (the verse), 'Vâstoshpati!' (MB. II, 6, I.)

20\. And with the seven last (texts) used at the driving away of
misfortune (see above, chap. I, 20, 21).

21\. After he has sacrificed, he should distribute Balis in the
different directions (of the horizon).

